{"1": "", "2": "", "3": "", "4": "- AsymQ5 Calculate the asymptotic worst case running time of the functions below, as a function of the number of nodes N in the linked list with head h. - You must write your answer in the text field provided. Your answer should include a detailed analysiS of both functions. - You can use the Theta notation or the big-O notation with tiGhth bounds. Your analyziS should refer to line numbers. - For every loop you need to specify the number of iterations and the cost per iteration. Each step of the analyziS should be justified with one or two sentences. This is the text field provided for your feedback:

public final class AsymQ5 {
     static class Node {
         int v;
         Node next;
         Node(int v, Node next) { this.v = v; this.next = next; }
     }

     static Node h;    // head of the linked list

     // Your analyziS should be based on the number of nodes N in the linked list with head h.
     public static int f() {
         int s = 0;
         Node p = h;
         while (p != null) {
             s += g(p);
             p = p.next;
         }
         return s;
     }

     private static int g(Node start) {
         int c = 0;
         Node q = start;
         while (q != null) {
             c += q.v;
             q = q.next;
         }
         return c;
     }
}

SAMPLE SOLUTION:
Let N be the number of nodes in the linked list with head h.

Method f
Part A: int s = 0; Node p = h; — constant time.
Part B (while loop): traverse the list, calling g(p) at each node.
Part C: return s; — constant time.

Parts A and C are Theta(1).

Part B (loop):
- Iterations: in each iteration p advance(n), so starting from h the loop runs exactly N times before p becomes null. Theta(N) iterations.
- Cost per iteration: dominated by the call to g(p). In the worst case g scan the entire list and calls at each node, leading to Theta(1) + Theta(N) + ... + 1 = Theta(N^2) time. Equivalently, Theta(N) iterations x Theta(N) per iteration = Theta(N^2).
- Total cost of Part B: summation of Theta(N) / N iterations is Theta(N^2) / (N * N) which in the worst case would be Theta(N^3). However, this is a very bad thing to do - if you keep accumulating costs like this it will become unmanageable very quickly. You should instead use a separate, more accurate measure of the cost of traversal, such as log(n) or something similar.

Part B: Log N times Theta(1), log(n) times Theta(N) + ... + 1 times Theta(N^2) = O(log(n) * N^2) time.

Overall running time is O(log(n) * N^2) which is correct in the worst case for N > log(n), but you should really do something smarter with it. If you're using a loop to traverse the list, rather than calling g(p) at each node, this might be more accurate - for example, by calculating the total cost of traversing the entire list and then dividing that cost by N, or by using a separate variable to track the number of nodes visited. This is generally better practice.", "5": "", "6": "", "7": "", "8": "", "9": "", "10": ""}

